<section xml:id="sec-CA-topics" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">

     <title>Topics in MA112 College Algebra</title>
    <p>
        Topics include solving linear and polynomial equations and inequalities, 
        simplifying and evaluating polynomial, rational, radical, piecewise-defined, 
        exponential and logarithmic expressions, graphing linear and quadratic functions, 
        and solving applied problems and systems of linear equations. 
    </p>
    <!--<xi:include href="exer-CA"/>-->
    <exercises xml:id="exer-CA">
        <title>What will I learn in MA112 College Algebra</title>
        <introduction>
          <p> 
            At the end of MA112, you should be able to do the following:
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <exercise>
        <title> Simplify Algebraic Expressions</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Simplify the following:
          </p>
          <ol cols="2">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>
                  3x^2-5(x+4)^2
                </m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>
                  \frac{6x^2-6}{2x^2-4x+2}
                </m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            a. <m>-2x^2-40x-80</m>; (b) <m>\frac{3(x+1)}{x-1}</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <ol>
              <li>
                  <m>3x^2-5(x+4)^2=3x^2-5(x+4)(x+4)=3x^2-5x^2-40x-80</m>
              </li>
              <li>
                <m>\frac{6x^2-6}{2x^2-4x+2}=
                  \frac{6(x+1)(x-1)}{2(x-1)(x-1)}=\frac{3(x+1)}{x-1}</m>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </solution>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
          <title>Solve Linear and Quadratic Equations</title>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Solve each of the following:
            </p>
            <ol>
              <li>
                  <m>4x-\frac{2}{3}(x+3)=\frac{1}{3}(x+12)</m>
              </li>
              <li>
                  <m>(x-4)(x+5)=36</m>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <hint>
            <p>
              Using a guess-and-check method does not qualify as understanding
            this concept.
            </p>
          </hint>
          <answer>
            <p>
              (a) <m>x=2</m>; (b) <m>x=7</m> or <m>x=-8</m>
            </p>
          </answer>
          <solution>
            <p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                      One method of solving this problem is to use the 
                      distributive property to get 
                      <m>4x-\frac{2x}{3}-2=\frac{x}{3}+4</m>. Adding
                      <m>2-\frac{x}{3}</m> to both sides gives 
                      <m>4x-\frac{2x}{3}-\frac{x}{3}=4+2</m> or <m>4x-x=6</m>. 
                      Thus, <m>3x=6</m> and <m>x=2</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    Expanding the left side, we get <m>x^2+x-20=36</m> which 
                    can be rewritten as <m>x^2+x-56=0</m>. Factoring the polynomial
                    gives us <m>(x-7)(x+8)=0</m> so that <m>x=7</m> or <m>x=-8</m>.
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
          <title>Work with exponents and radicals</title>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Simplify the following expressions:
            </p>
            <ol>
              <li>
                  <m>\sqrt{9x^2 y^6}</m>
              </li>
              <li>
                  <m>\left(\frac{24x^8}{15x^3}\right)^{-2}</m>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p>
              (a) <m>3xy^3</m>; (b) <m>\frac{4y^2}{21x^2}</m>;  
              (c) <m>\frac{25}{64x^{10}}</m>
            </p>
          </answer>
          <solution>
            <p>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <m>\sqrt{9x^2 y^6}=\sqrt{9}\sqrt{x^2}\sqrt{y^6}=3xy^3</m>
            </li>
              <li>
                  <md>
                    <mrow>\left(\frac{2x}{3}\right)^3 \left(\frac{9y^2}{14x^5}\right)
                    \amp=\left(\frac{(2x)^3}{3^3}\right) \left(\frac{9y^2}{14x^5}\right)</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{8x^3\cdot 9y^2}{27\cdot 14x^5}
                    =\frac{4y^2}{21x^2}</mrow>
                    </md>
              </li>
              <li>
                  <m>\left(\frac{24x^8}{15x^3}\right)^{-2}
                    =\left(\frac{8x^5}{5}\right)^{-2}=\left(\frac{64x^{10}}{25}\right)^{-1}
                    =\frac{25}{64x^{10}}
                  </m>
              </li>
            </ol>
            </p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
          <title>Determine an Equation for a Line</title>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Determine an equation for the line that passes through the point
              <m>(10,4)</m> and is perpendicular to the line <m>y=5x-12</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p>
              Possible solutions include <m>y=-\frac{1}{5}x+6</m> and <m>x+5y=30</m>.
            </p>
          </answer>
          <solution>
            <p>
              In order for the line to be perpendicular to <m>y=5x-12</m>, the 
              slope of the line must be <m>-\frac{1}{5}</m>. We can then use this slope 
              together with the point <m>(10,4)</m> to find the 
              <m>y</m>-intercept by solving <m>4=-\frac{1}{5}(10)+b</m>. Another option 
              is to substitute into the point-slope form to get, <m>y-4=-\frac{1}{5}(x-10)</m>.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
          <title>Solve systems of linear equations</title>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Find the ordered pair that satisfies the system:
              <md>
                <mrow> x+2y&amp;=25</mrow>
                <mrow> 10x+15y&amp;=210 </mrow>
              </md>
            </p>

          </statement>
          <hint>
            You should be able to solve this problem algebraically 
            either by elimination or by the substitution method. Using 
            a guess-and-check strategy does not count as understanding 
            this concept. 
          </hint>
          <answer>  
            <p>
              <m>(x,y)=(9,8)</m>; that is, <m>x=9</m> and <m>y=8</m>.
            </p>
          </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
          <title>Factor polynomials and solve polynomial equations</title>
          <statement> 
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Factor <m>28x^3y^5-14x^5y^2</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Solve <m>81x^4=16</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p>
              (a) <m>14x^3y^2(2y^3-x^2)</m>; (b) <m>x=\pm\frac{2}{3}</m>
            </p>
          </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
          <title>Combine and evaluate functions</title>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Let <m>f(x)=x+3</m> and <m>g(x)=2x^2-x+4</m>. Determine the following:
            </p>
            <ol cols="2">
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>g(10)</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>(f+g)(x)</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>(fg)(2)</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>g\circ f(x)</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p>
              (a) <m>g(10)=194</m>; (b) <m>(f+g)(x)=2x^2+7</m>;
              (c) <m>(fg)(2)=50</m>; 
              (d) <m>f\circ g(x)=2x^2+11x+19</m>
            </p>
          </answer>
          <solution>
            <p>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>g(10)=2(10)^2-10+4=200-10+4=194</m>
                </p>
              </li> 
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>(f+g)(x)=f(x)+g(x)=(x+3)+(2x^2-x+4)=2x^2+7</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>(fg)(2)=f(2)g(2)=5\cdot 10=50</m>
                </p>
              </li> 
              <li>
                <p>
                <md><mrow>f\circ g(x)\amp=2(x+3)^2-(x+3)+4</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=2x^2+12x+18-x-3+4=2x^2+11x+19</mrow></md>  
                </p>
              </li> 
            </ol>
          </p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>
      </exercises>
    </section>